I wanted an exercise that would help me understand how different parts of the development interact. So I came up with a simple component

<!--more-->

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-56" src="https://myaemjourney.files.wordpress.com/2016/08/2016-07-28-11_32_15-home-e1470304076789.png" alt="counter_component" width="193" height="121" />

It is quite simple. It's a counter which you control with the buttons. The value of the counter is stored in the repository so it doesn't reset when you close the page. This is a silly example but I can image it becoming useful when creating a more complex component that require interaction between a component and the repository.
<h3>Journey</h3>
<ol>
 	<li>Create folder structure, including clientlibs.</li>
 	<li>Creating a model.</li>
 	<li>Creating a servlet.</li>
 	<li>Creating the html.</li>
 	<li>Creating the JavaScript.</li>
</ol>
<h3>Folder structure</h3>
<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-57" src="https://myaemjourney.files.wordpress.com/2016/08/folder_structure.png" alt="folder_structure" width="257" height="285" />

I created the archetype following the instructions listed <a href="http://localhost:8090/wordpress/2016/07/14/creating-an-archetype/">here</a>. I got the <em>clientlibs</em> structure from the component called <em>colctrl. </em>For this project I did not apply any CSS, just JavaScript.
<h3></h3>
<h3>Model</h3>
The model is in charge of making sure that the data node exists in the repository, and create it if it doesn't. In folder
<pre>/aem-startup.core/src/main/java/com/valtech/aemstartup/core/models/</pre>
I created a file named CounterModel.java with the following logic:

[code language="java" collapse="true"]
package com.valtech.aemstartup.core.models;

import javax.jcr.Node;
import javax.jcr.RepositoryException;
import javax.jcr.Session;
import org.apache.sling.api.resource.Resource;
import org.slf4j.Logger;
import org.slf4j.LoggerFactory;
import com.adobe.cq.sightly.WCMUse;
import com.day.cq.commons.jcr.JcrConstants;
import com.day.cq.commons.jcr.JcrUtil;

public class CounterModel extends WCMUse{

	protected Logger log = LoggerFactory.getLogger(this.getClass());

	@Override
	public void activate() {
		log.info(&quot;Entering the Counter Model&quot;);
		Resource componentResource = getResourceResolver().getResource(&quot;/content/aemstartup/data&quot;);
		if(componentResource == null)
		{
			log.info(&quot;Data node not found. Start creating it&quot;);

			Session session = getResourceResolver().adaptTo(Session.class);

			//Create the Node
			try {
				Node node = JcrUtil.createPath(&quot;/content/aemstartup/data&quot;, JcrConstants.NT_UNSTRUCTURED,session);
				node.setProperty(&quot;value&quot;, 0);
				log.info(&quot;Node created successfully. Node info: &quot; + node.toString());
				session.save();
			} catch (RepositoryException e) {
				log.info(&quot;Creating node not successful: &quot; + e.getMessage());
				e.printStackTrace();
			}
		}
	}
}

[/code]

This model initialises the data node and stores it under the content folder. The HTML will now get the value from this node, and the buttons will interact with it through a JavaScript-Ajax-Servlet.
<h3>Servlet</h3>
The servlet is in charge of updating the values of the node created by the model. This is done with a post method. The new value of the node is then passed back to the ajax as a JSON object. In folder
<pre>/aem-startup.core/src/main/java/com/valtech/aemstartup/core/servlets/</pre>
I create file CounterServlet.java with the following logic:

[code language="java" collapse="true"]
package com.valtech.aemstartup.core.servlets;

import java.io.IOException;
import javax.jcr.Node;
import javax.jcr.Session;
import javax.servlet.ServletException;
import org.apache.felix.scr.annotations.Component;
import org.apache.felix.scr.annotations.Property;
import org.apache.felix.scr.annotations.Service;
import org.apache.felix.scr.annotations.sling.SlingServlet;
import org.apache.sling.api.SlingHttpServletRequest;
import org.apache.sling.api.SlingHttpServletResponse;
import org.apache.sling.api.resource.Resource;
import org.apache.sling.api.resource.ResourceResolver;
import org.apache.sling.api.servlets.SlingAllMethodsServlet;
import org.apache.sling.commons.json.JSONArray;
import org.apache.sling.commons.json.JSONObject;
import org.slf4j.Logger;
import org.slf4j.LoggerFactory;


@Component(metatype = true)
@SlingServlet(
		methods = {&quot;POST&quot;},
		generateComponent = false
		)
@Service
public class CounterServlet extends SlingAllMethodsServlet {
	private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;

	@Property(name = &quot;sling.servlet.paths&quot;)
	public static final String SERVLET_PATH = &quot;/services/counterServlet&quot;;

	@Property(name = &quot;sling.auth.requirements&quot;, propertyPrivate = false)
	private static final String[] AUTH_REQUIREMENT = { &quot;+&quot; + SERVLET_PATH };

	protected Logger log = LoggerFactory.getLogger(this.getClass());

	@Override
	protected void doPost(SlingHttpServletRequest req, SlingHttpServletResponse res) throws ServletException, IOException {

		res.setContentType(&quot;application/json&quot;);
		JSONArray dataArray = new JSONArray();

		log.debug(&quot;Post method in servlet&quot;);

		String sign = req.getParameter(&quot;sign&quot;);

		log.info(&quot;Sign: &quot; + sign);

		try {

			String resourcePath = &quot;/content/aemstartup/data&quot;;

			ResourceResolver obj2 = req.getResourceResolver();

			Resource res2 = obj2.getResource(resourcePath);

			Node node=res2.adaptTo(Node.class);

			log.info(&quot;Node: &quot; + node.toString());

			Session session=node.getSession();

			String oldVal = node.getProperty(&quot;value&quot;).getValue().toString();

			long newVal;

			if(sign.equals(&quot;plus&quot;)){
				newVal = Integer.parseInt(oldVal) + 1;
			}
			else if(sign.equals(&quot;minus&quot;)){
				newVal = Integer.parseInt(oldVal) - 1;
			}
			else{
				newVal = 0;
			}

			node.setProperty(&quot;value&quot;,  newVal);

			session.save();

			dataArray.put(new JSONObject().put(&quot;newVal&quot;,newVal));

			dataArray.write(res.getWriter());

		} catch (Exception e){
			log.info(&quot;Exception: &quot; + e.getMessage());
			throw new ServletException();
		}
	}
}
[/code]

<h3>HTML</h3>
Now we have the core ready for the component. Then we start creating the front end.

[code language="html" collapse="true"]
&lt;sly data-sly-use.counter=&quot;com.valtech.aemstartup.core.models.CounterModel&quot;/&gt;

&lt;sly data-sly-use.clientLib=&quot;${'/libs/granite/sightly/templates/clientlib.html'}&quot; data-sly-unwrap/&gt;
&lt;sly data-sly-call=&quot;${clientLib.js @ categories='aemstartup.components'}&quot; data-sly-unwrap/&gt;




&lt;h2 id=&quot;bigcounter&quot;&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;




&lt;button id=&quot;plus&quot; &gt; + &lt;/button&gt;
&lt;button id=&quot;minus&quot;&gt; - &lt;/button&gt;
&lt;button id=&quot;reset&quot;&gt; reset &lt;/button&gt;
[/code]

The first line calls the model I just created, and the next two lines include the clientlibs. The rest is the basic HTML.
<h3>Javascript</h3>
Within the clientlibs folder I create a text file called js.txt which only contains one line:
<pre>logic.js</pre>
This file points to the javascripts that should be run and in what order. In our case we only run one script, called logic.js.

[code language="javascript" collapsed="true"]
$(document).on(&quot;click&quot;, &quot;#minus&quot;, function() {
	var sign = &quot;minus&quot;;
	$.ajax({
		url: &quot;/services/counterServlet&quot;,
		type: &quot;POST&quot;,
		data: {
			sign: sign
		},
		success: function (data) {

			var response = data[0].newVal;
			document.getElementById(&quot;bigcounter&quot;).innerHTML = response;
		},
		error: function () {
			alert(&quot;Error!&quot;);
		}
	});
});
[/code]

This code example is the action for button with id="minus". The action is sent as a string parameter with the ajax to the servlet to determine whether to increase, decrease or reset the counter. The response is the new value of the counter, and the counter is updated accordingly.
<h3>Result</h3>
The result is a component that has connection to the repository, both in the form of a model and a servlet. The model runs every time the page is reloaded whereas the servlet is called when a button is pressed. The value of the label is updated without refreshing the page, using Ajax. I can imagine using this solution as a baseline when creating components that require this kind of connection to the JCR.

I was in a position where I wanted to improve a title component which is rendered with JSP. The user enters some text, and then chooses between five different headers. Instead of a drop down list with the names of the headers, I wanted the user to click an image with a preview of the header
<!--more-->

This was done with screen captions of the headers:
<img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-72" src="https://myaemjourney.files.wordpress.com/2016/08/headers.png?w=736" alt="headers" width="736" height="753" />
