<h3>Workflow</h3>
The main purpose of this exercise is to start a workflow programmatically. So the workflow I created is rudimentary, just a notification that is sent to two users that come out of the box with AEM: Aaron McDonald and Charlotte Capp.

Open
<pre><a href="http://localhost:4502/libs/cq/workflow/content/console.html">http://localhost:4502/libs/cq/workflow/content/console.html</a></pre>
and press "new" and give your workflow a title. Then you can start editing the workflow. I've created two "participant steps" for this example:

<img class="aligncenter wp-image-108 size-medium" src="https://myaemjourney.files.wordpress.com/2016/08/participantstep.png?w=157" alt="participantstep" width="157" height="300" />

<img class="aligncenter wp-image-109 size-medium" src="https://myaemjourney.files.wordpress.com/2016/08/workflow.png?w=282" alt="workflow" width="282" height="300" />

I configured the steps and chose these two users at random.
<h3>Testing your workflow</h3>
To see if your workflow is working you can select it and press start. The workflow showed above does not require any payload at the moment, so in payload path you can enter just a forward slash. Then you open localhost:4502 and use the impersonator feature:

<img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-111" src="https://myaemjourney.files.wordpress.com/2016/08/impersonator.png?w=300" alt="impersonator" width="300" height="210" />

Select the person that is involved in current step in the workflow (make sure that said person has at least read permissions on the system. That can be modified <a href="http://localhost:4502/useradmin">here</a>).
<h3>Component</h3>
Like I said, this component is really simple as the whole point is the relationship between the component and the workflow, rather than some elaborate visual component.

